{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"39433241-f561-458f-9881-73a15c908e16","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**. Here's why:\n\n| Command | What it does |\n|---|---|\n| `dotnet workload update` | Downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. This is what you want after an SDK update. |\n| `dotnet workload repair` | **Re-installs** workloads at their current versions. Useful if files are corrupted or missing, but won't pull newer versions. |\n\nSince your SDK changed, the workload versions need to catch up:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\n```\n\nIf the build still fails after that, run `dotnet workload list` to confirm the `maui` workload is installed, and check the build output for specific errors.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3521fed9-7e45-4780-b49b-eebc6bcd56bf","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` for fixing build issues after a .NET SDK update. This is a general knowledge question — I don't need to explore any codebase.","outputTokens":246,"requestId":"9BC3:335471:5C4B388:6782CCC:69EC0DE7"},"id":"5e299cbb-bb73-450a-b682-1e41153d9ff9","timestamp":"2026-04-25T00:42:22.638Z","parentId":"cbcdc156-61d3-4727-ac08-ac1a79727d38"}
